Landmark Stream → Sequence Buffer → Feature Encoding → Label Generation → Training Set → Model Training → Evaluation
1) INPUT CONTRACT (FROM YOUR EXISTING CODE)

Assume you already output per frame:

{
  "t": float,
  "face": [468 x 3],
  "left_hand": [21 x 3] | null,
  "right_hand": [21 x 3] | null
}
Required preprocessing (before anything else):
Normalize coordinates (face-centered or screen-normalized)
Fill missing hands with:
zeros
mask flag (VERY important)
2) SEQUENCE BUFFER (CRITICAL FIX)

You should NOT train per-frame.

Implement:
Rolling buffer of 60 frames
Update every 15–30 frames
sequence = shape(60, raw_landmark_dim)
3) FEATURE ENCODING (THIS IS THE MAIN UPGRADE)

Raw landmarks → weak signal
Engineered features → strong signal

3.1 Face Encoding
A. Static geometry (per frame)
Mouth width
Mouth openness
Eye openness (L/R)
Eyebrow height
Head tilt (approx from key points)
B. Temporal (per frame)
velocity = current - previous
acceleration = velocity - prev_velocity
3.2 Hand Encoding (THIS IS WHERE YOU WIN)

For each hand:

A. Motion intensity
hand_motion = sum(||joint_t - joint_t-1||)
B. Finger states

For each finger:

Extended (1/0)
Curled (distance tip → palm)
C. Gesture embedding (lightweight)

Derive:

OPEN_HAND
CLOSED_FIST
POINTING
PINCH
UNKNOWN

Rule-based is fine initially.

D. Behavioral signals
Movement variance (over 60 frames)
Frequency (FFT or zero-crossings)
Symmetry (left vs right)
3.3 Interaction Features (UNDERRATED, HIGH VALUE)

These dramatically improve behavior inference:

Hand ↔ face distance
Hand touching face (binary)
Hands crossing midline
Head movement vs hand movement correlation
3.4 Final Feature Vector

Per frame:

F ≈ 300–1200 features

Per sequence:

X.shape = (60, F)
4) LABEL GENERATION (YOUR CURRENT WEAK POINT)

You likely don’t have strong labels—fix this.

4.1 Multi-Head Labeling (recommended)

Instead of one label, use:

y = {
  "emotion": one_hot(6–8 classes),
  "engagement": scalar (0–1),
  "nervousness": scalar (0–1),
  "gesture_class": multi-label
}
4.2 Auto-labeling (scalable approach)
Emotion (face-driven proxies)
Smile → happy
Eye widen → surprise
Low movement → neutral/sad
Behavior (hand-driven)
High variance → nervous
Repetitive motion → fidgeting
Stillness → disengaged
4.3 Bootstrap with pretrained tools

Use:

DeepFace
OpenFace

These give:

Emotion probabilities
Action Units

Treat them as:

soft labels (not ground truth)
5) DATASET CONSTRUCTION

Convert sequences into:

X = (N, 60, F)
y = (N, targets)
Normalize:
Per-feature standardization
Clip outliers
6) MODEL (FOCUSED ON TEMPORAL LEARNING)

You don’t need anything exotic initially.

Option A — Strong baseline
2-layer LSTM → Dense → Multi-head outputs
Option B — Better
Temporal Transformer → Multi-head heads
Output heads:
Emotion (softmax)
Engagement (regression)
Nervousness (regression)
Gesture class (multi-label sigmoid)
7) TRAINING STRATEGY
Loss:
L = L_emotion + L_engagement + L_nervousness + L_gesture
Key improvements:
Class balancing
Label smoothing (for noisy labels)
Temporal dropout (drop random frames)
8) EVALUATION (DON’T SKIP THIS)

Measure separately:

Emotion accuracy
Gesture F1 score
Behavior regression error

Also check:

Temporal consistency (predictions shouldn’t flicker)
9) REAL-TIME DEPLOYMENT ADJUSTMENTS
Use rolling predictions
Apply EMA smoothing:
pred = alpha * current + (1-alpha) * prev
10) WHAT WILL ACTUALLY IMPROVE YOUR MODEL

If you do only 3 things:

1. Switch to sequence-based training
2. Add hand-derived behavioral features
3. Use multi-head outputs instead of single label

You’ll see a massive jump in performance.

Bottom line

You don’t need new tracking.
You need:

Better features + better labels + temporal modeling